From a9189a078000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Mykola Lysenko <mykolal@meta.com>
Date: Tue, 21 Apr 2026 21:33:59 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] libbpf: handle duplicate BTF types in CO-RE relocations

On UML, glibc headers included by UML driver files (arch/um/drivers/)
produce duplicate BTF types in vmlinux.  These are structurally
equivalent types with the same name and size but different BTF IDs
(e.g. struct in6_addr with member 'in6_u' vs '__in6_u', or
struct sockaddr_un appearing twice).

This causes two failures:

1. btf_relocate: when loading bpf_testmod.ko, btf_relocate() validates
   the module BTF against vmlinux BTF.  Multiple base types with the
   same name and size are treated as a fatal error (-EINVAL), preventing
   bpf_testmod's BTF from being registered in /sys/kernel/btf/.  Without
   module BTF, veristat fails with -ESRCH for all programs referencing
   bpf_testmod types.

2. relo_core: when libbpf performs BPF_CORE_TYPE_ID_TARGET relocations,
   two matching candidates with different BTF type IDs trigger the
   ambiguity check, returning -EINVAL.

In both cases the duplicates are structurally equivalent — they passed
the same matching criteria.  The difference in BTF ID or member name is
an artifact of duplicate type registration, not a real ambiguity.

Fix both by keeping the first (canonical) match and skipping subsequent
duplicates with a debug message.

Signed-off-by: Mykola Lysenko <mykolal@meta.com>
---
 tools/lib/bpf/btf_relocate.c | 24 ++++++++++++------------
 tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c    | 12 ++++++++++++
 2 files changed, 24 insertions(+), 12 deletions(-)

diff --git a/tools/lib/bpf/btf_relocate.c b/tools/lib/bpf/btf_relocate.c
index 53d1f3541..32b27bb52 100644
--- a/tools/lib/bpf/btf_relocate.c
+++ b/tools/lib/bpf/btf_relocate.c
@@ -341,19 +341,19 @@ static int btf_relocate_map_distilled_base(struct btf_relocate *r)
 			}
 			if (r->id_map[dist_info->id] &&
 			    r->id_map[dist_info->id] != BTF_IS_EMBEDDED) {
-				/* we already have a match; this tells us that
-				 * multiple base types of the same name
-				 * have the same size, since for cases where
-				 * multiple types have the same name we match
-				 * on name and size.  In this case, we have
-				 * no way of determining which to relocate
-				 * to in base BTF, so error out.
+				/* We already have a match; multiple base types
+				 * of the same name have the same size.  This
+				 * can happen on UML where glibc headers are
+				 * included alongside kernel headers, producing
+				 * structurally equivalent but differently-named
+				 * duplicates (e.g. struct in6_addr with member
+				 * 'in6_u' vs '__in6_u').  Keep the first match
+				 * and skip subsequent candidates.
 				 */
-				pr_warn("distilled base BTF type '%s' [%u], size %u has multiple candidates of the same size (ids [%u, %u]) in base BTF\n",
-					base_info.name, dist_info->id,
-					base_t->size, id, r->id_map[dist_info->id]);
-				err = -EINVAL;
-				goto done;
+				pr_debug("distilled base BTF type '%s' [%u], size %u has multiple candidates (ids [%u, %u]); keeping first\n",
+					 base_info.name, dist_info->id,
+					 base_t->size, id, r->id_map[dist_info->id]);
+				continue;
 			}
 			/* map id and name */
 			r->id_map[dist_info->id] = id;
diff --git a/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c b/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c
index 6ae3f2a15..9de6cfec0 100644
--- a/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c
+++ b/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c
@@ -1385,6 +1385,18 @@ int bpf_core_calc_relo_insn(const char *prog_name,
 			return -EINVAL;
 		} else if (cand_res.poison != targ_res->poison ||
 			   cand_res.new_val != targ_res->new_val) {
+			/* TYPE_ID_TARGET: duplicate types with different BTF IDs
+			 * are safe to resolve to the first (canonical) match.
+			 * See btf_relocate.c for the same approach.
+			 */
+			if (relo->kind == BPF_CORE_TYPE_ID_TARGET &&
+			    !cand_res.poison && !targ_res->poison) {
+				pr_debug("prog '%s': relo #%d: TYPE_ID_TARGET ambiguity: keeping first candidate (id %llu), skipping duplicate (id %llu)\n",
+					 prog_name, relo_idx,
+					 (unsigned long long)targ_res->new_val,
+					 (unsigned long long)cand_res.new_val);
+				continue;
+			}
 			/* all candidates should result in the same relocation
 			 * decision and value, otherwise it's dangerous to
 			 * proceed due to ambiguity
-- 
2.34.1

